Management groups themselves do not directly contain resources but organize subscriptions that contain resources. This indirect arrangement allows grouping of various resource types across subscriptions.

For example, a management group may include subscriptions that contain:

* Virtual machines
* Databases
* Storage accounts
* Networking resources

A real-life use case is a company managing multiple applications across subscriptions. All production-related subscriptions can be grouped under a “Production Management Group”.

Another example is applying policies like restricting certain VM sizes across all subscriptions under a group.

This structure allows organizations to manage diverse resources efficiently through hierarchical grouping.
